  "body": "Commit: https://github.com/superfluid-finance/protocol-monorepo/commit/677048c5819900bbac3f5a0eefd31f0807a8d77b#diff-86c81041870e5b8a71779503041e9e4b65805426e763829d48e99a8e707ea8a2R799-R804\r\n\r\nTo reproduce:\r\n- git clone the monorepo\r\n- do yarn install && yarn build\r\n- cd into packages/sdk-core and run `yarn test`\r\n- it will revert with: \"Transaction reverted: trying to deploy a contract whose code is too large\"\r\n\r\nI have tried setting `allowUnlimitedContractSize` to true and it still breaks.\r\n\r\nSo from what I can tell, this is occurring when I try to deploy a contract which is **`120894`** bytes.\r\n\r\nThis is understandable given that the size of the contract exceeds the 24kb maximum contract size constraint. \r\n\r\nHowever, the previous size of the contract was: **`120709`** and there were no errors being thrown even though `allowUnlimitedContractSize` was unset (`false` by default).\r\n\r\nThe highlighted code linked above leads to this error, if you comment out the code, the code size is reduced and it works as expected again, even though the code size is still well above the limit.",
